    "narrative": "For today\u2019s slate, our offensive engine is centered around **Mickey Moniak** (75.98) and **Brice Turang** (75.06), both of whom leverage elite speed metrics against favorable matchups. **Mickey Moniak** is our top play, as he benefits from a highly favorable platoon split and a slow delivery from Buehler, creating significant theft upside that aligns with our organizational priority on stolen bases. **Brice Turang** earns his spot at the top of the order against Irvin, J, maximizing his high-contact profile and on-base potential to drive our R and SB categories. While **Vinnie Pasquantino** (72.92) provides a robust floor against Martin, owners should monitor the 31% rain risk, which could shorten his outing or result in a high-leverage pinch-hit situation should the game be delayed.\n\nThe decision to bench **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** (47.75) was the most difficult pivot of the day, as his base projection remains high, but his inefficiency against Matz\u2014coupled with a brutal dynamic platoon disadvantage\u2014made him a sub-optimal start relative to the rest of the outfield. **James Wood** (50.18) maintains his spot despite a challenging matchup against Ashby because his high stolen base potential (87% efficiency) is vital for our scarcity needs. Meanwhile, **Tyler Soderstrom** (63.69) continues to hold value due to favorable SP skill metrics against Holmes, C, proving that even with a neutral park factor, his current form warrants a start over the riskier options on our bench like **Kyle Karros** (49.57) or **Alex Freeland** (50.90), both of whom were suppressed by unfavorable batting orders. **Gabriel Moreno** (46.93) and **Dalton Rushing** (55.76) remain our primary catchers, with **Dalton Rushing** showing slight upside if wind conditions in his park facilitate extra-base potential, though both require careful management as we balance game caps.",
